Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio.
• Debt is taken from the liabilities side. In the Balance Sheet the only provided liability is the Total Current Liabilities of 5,637,910.70.
• Owner’s Equity is given as 16,099,532.29.
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Debt ÷ Owner’s Equity = 5,637,910.70 ÷ 16,099,532.29 ≈ 0.35.

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin.
• From the Income Statement, the Net Profit is 99,532.29 and the Total Revenue is 836,813.79.
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit ÷ Total Revenue) × 100 = (99,532.29 ÷ 836,813.79) × 100 ≈ 11.89%.

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.
• From the Cash Flow Statement, the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities is –1,919,526.63.
• The Total Current Liabilities (from the Balance Sheet) are 5,637,910.70.
• Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio = –1,919,526.63 ÷ 5,637,910.70 ≈ –0.34.

Thus, the final answer is:
{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.35",

    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-0.34"
  }
